{{hatnote|This article is about the Gaulish god. For other uses, see [[Alaunus (disambiguation)]].}}

'''Alaunus''' or '''Alaunius''' was a [[Gallo-Roman religion|Gaulish god]] of healing and prophecy. His name is known from inscriptions found in [[Lurs, Alpes-de-Haute-Provence]] in southern [[France]]<ref>Where it appears in Greek in the dative case: {{lang|grc|Αλανειουι}}, ''Alaneioui''.</ref> and in [[Mannheim]] in western [[Germany]]. In the latter inscription, Alaunus is [[interpretatio graeca|used as an epithet]] of [[Mercury (mythology)|Mercury]].<ref>''L'Arbre Celtique''. "[http://www.arbre-celtique.com/approfondissements/divinites/inventaire-div/div_liste.php?nomdiv=Alaunus Alaunus]" and "[http://www.arbre-celtique.com/approfondissements/divinites/inventaire-div/div_liste.php?nomdiv=Alaunius Alaunius]".</ref> The name of this deity is also found as a [[Celtic placenames|placename]] both of [[toponym|sites]] and [[hydronym|rivers]]. Its feminine form '''Alauna''' appears in the Roman-era names of [[Valognes]] in [[Normandy]], [[Alauna Carvetiorum|Maryport]] and [[Alavana|Watercrook]] in [[Cumbria]], [[Alcester]] in [[Warwickshire]], [[Ardoch fort|Ardoch]] in [[Perthshire]], and [[Learchild]] and the [[River Aln]] in [[Northumberland]].

The etymology of the name remains uncertain. Some connect it with the [[Proto-Celtic]] root [[linguistic reconstruction|reconstructed]] as {{nowrap|*''alo-''}} ("feed, raise, nurture"), but [[Ranko Matasović|Matasović]] discounts it.<ref>Matasović, Ranko. ''Etymological Dictionary of Proto-Celtic'', {{nowrap|p. 30.}} Kloninklijke Brill (Leiden), 2009.</ref> [[W. F. H. Nicolaisen|Nicolaisen]] connected the various hydronyms to the unrelated [[Proto-Indo-European language|Proto-Indo-European]] root reconstructed as *''el-'' or *''ol-'' meaning "to flow or stream".<ref>Nicolaisen, W.F.H. ''Scottish Place-names: Their Study and Significance'', pp.&nbsp;186&nbsp;ff. Anova Books (Batsford), 1976. Reprinted 1986. {{ISBN|978-0-7134-5234-1}}.</ref> Monaghan posits an unrelated [[Celtic mythology|Celtic]] river goddess Alauna, found in [[Brittany]].<ref>Monaghan, P. ''The Encyclopedia of Celtic Mythology and Folklore'', p.&nbsp;13. Facts on File (New York), 2002.</ref>

