[[File:MERS Coronavirus Particles (14702511068).jpg|thumb|MERS Coronavirus Particles found in the [[Lumen (anatomy)|lumen]] of the [[endoplasmic reticulum]] in an infected MRC-5 cell]] '''MRC-5''' ([[Medical Research Council (United Kingdom)|Medical Research Council]] cell strain 5) is a diploid human [[cell culture]] line composed of [[fibroblast]]s derived from lung tissue of a 14 week old aborted caucasian male fetus.<ref name=atcc>{{cite web|title=MRC-5 (ATCC® CCL-171™)|url=http://www.atcc.org/Products/All/CCL-171.aspx|accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref><ref name=Coriell>{{cite web|title=AG05965-D Fibroblast from Skin, Lung|url=https://catalog.coriell.org/0/Sections/Search/Sample_Detail.aspx?Ref=AG05965-D|accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref> The cell line was isolated by J.P. Jacobs and colleagues in September 1966 from the 7th population doubling of the original strain, and MRC-5 cells themselves are known to reach [[Cellular senescence|senescence]] in around 45 population doublings. <ref name=Coriell/> <ref name=Jacobs1970>{{cite journal |last=Jacobs |first=J. P. |last2=Jones |first2=C. M. |last3=Baille |first3=J. P. |title=Characteristics of a Human Diploid Cell Designated MRC-5 |journal=Nature |date=1970 |volume=227 |pages=168 |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/227168a0}}</ref> <ref name=Jacobs1976>{{cite journal |last=Jacobs |first=J. P. |title=The Status of Human Diploid Cell Strain MRC-5 as an Approved Substrate for the Production of Viral Vaccines |journal=Journal of Biological Standardization |date=1976 |volume=4 |pages=97–99 |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0092115776900184}}</ref>
==Applications== MRC-5 cells are used to produce several vaccines including [[MMR vaccine|MMR]], [[Varicella vaccine|Varicella]] and [[Polio vaccine|Polio]]. Infected MRC-5 cells secrete the virus, and can be cultured in large volumes suitable for commercial production.
