A '''microkeratome''' is a precision [[surgery|surgical]] instrument with an oscillating blade designed for creating the [[cornea]]l flap in [[LASIK]] or [[Automated lamellar keratoplasty|ALK surgery]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Xia LK, Yu J, Chai GR, Wang D, Li Y | title = Comparison of the femtosecond laser and mechanical microkeratome for flap cutting in LASIK | journal = International Journal of Ophthalmology | volume = 8 | issue = 4 | pages = 784–90 | date = August 2015 | pmid = 26309880 | pmc = 4539628 | doi = 10.3980/j.issn.2222-3959.2015.04.25 }}</ref> The normal human cornea varies from around 500 to 600 micrometres in thickness; and in the LASIK procedure, the microkeratome creates an 83 to 200 micrometre thick flap. This piece of equipment is used all around the world to cut the cornea flap. The microkeratome is also used in [[Corneal_transplantation#DSEK.2FDSAEK.2FDMEK|Descemet's stripping automated endothelial keratoplasty (DSAEK)]], where it is used to slice a thin layer from the back of the donor cornea, which is then transplanted into the posterior cornea of the recipient.<ref name="Stuart">{{cite journal |author=Stuart AJ, Virgili G, Shortt AJ |title= Descemet's membrane endothelial keratoplasty versus Descemet's stripping automated endothelial keratoplasty for corneal endothelial failure |journal=Cochrane Database Syst Rev|volume= |issue=3|pages= CD012097 |date=2016 |doi= 10.1002/14651858.CD012097}}</ref> It was invented by [[Jose Barraquer]] and Cesar Carlos Carriazo in the 1950s in Colombia.<ref>{{cite web | title = José I. Barraquer, MD | url = http://www.ascrs.org/honorees/jos%C3%A9-i-barraquer-md | publisher = American Society of Cataract and Refractive Surgery | work = ASCRS Ophthalmology Hall of Fame | date = 1999 }}</ref><ref name="pmid22496438">{{cite journal | vauthors = Reinstein DZ, Archer TJ, Gobbe M | title = The history of LASIK | journal = Journal of Refractive Surgery | volume = 28 | issue = 4 | pages = 291–8 | date = April 2012 | pmid = 22496438 | doi = 10.3928/1081597X-20120229-01 }}</ref>
