'''Teledentistry''' is the use of [[information technology]] and [[telecommunications]] for [[dentistry|dental care]], consultation,<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=11323836 |year=2000 |last1=Clark |first1=GT |title=Teledentistry: What is it now, and what will it be tomorrow? |volume=28 |issue=2 |pages=121–7 |journal=Journal of the California Dental Association}}</ref> education, and public awareness (compare [[telehealth]] and [[telemedicine]]).
== History == In 1994, the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defence]] introduced the Total Dental Access Program (TDA) for the Army.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rocca|first=M. A.|last2=Kudryk,|first2=V. L.|last3=Pajak|first3=J. C.|last4=Morris|first4=T|date=1999|title=The evolution of a teledentistry system within the Department of Defense|journal=Proceedings / AMIA ... Annual Symposium. AMIA Symposium|location=Frederick, MD, USA.|volume=|pages=921–4|issn=1531-605X|pmc=2232632|pmid=10566495|postscript=|ref=|separator=}}</ref> The goals of TDA were to increase soldier’s access to care and reduce associated costs. At the time, they used what was called the [[Plain old telephone system|plain-old-telephone-system]] (POTS).
In the early nineteen nineties, videoconferencing, e-mail, [[fax]], and telephone calls were used but more recently , video conferencing and high-quality image transfer have become easily accessible. These, and the considerable improvements in digital camera technology, have provide radical new opportunities.
Nearly a third of all Americans don’t visit a dentist regularly enough, according to the Gallup-Healthways Well-Being Index.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.medicaldaily.com/oral-health-isnt-much-americans-concern-poll-finds-one-third-didnt-see-dentist-last-year-279468|title=Oral Health Isn't Much Of Americans' Concern, Poll Finds: One-Third Didn’t See The Dentist Last Year|date=2014-04-29|work=Medical Daily|access-date=2017-11-27|language=en}}</ref> There are many reasons for this, most notably; affordability, access and fear.
== Benefits == Teledentistry can provide easier, cheaper and less intimidating way to connect with dentistry. Teledentistry can also be used to assist general dentists with speciality work<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nidcr.nih.gov/Research/ResearchResults/ScienceBriefs/Archive/archive2008/December/Teledentistry.htm|title=Teledentistry Shows Potential to Assist Rural Communities|date=December 24, 2008|publisher=NIH}}</ref> and improve services to underserved populations such as in rural or less developed areas.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=12699048 |year=2003 |last1=Chen |first1=Jung-Wei |last2=Hob-Dell |first2=Martin H. |last3=Dunn |first3=Kim |last4=Johnson |first4=Kathy A. |last5=Zhang |first5=Jiajie |title=Teledentistry and its use in dental education |volume=134 |issue=3 |pages=342–6 |journal=Journal of the American Dental Association |url=http://jada.ada.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=12699048 |doi=10.14219/jada.archive.2003.0164}}</ref>
